Both outputs are in place.

**Headline finding:** the dominant signal in this 50,000-patient prostate-cancer cohort is that **treatment_enzalutamide** raises objective response from ~17% to ~80% (adjusted OR ≈ 20) but only in patients meeting all four of `mcrpc=0 AND ar_v7_positive=0 AND brca2_mutation=0 AND msi_high=0` (n=15,681, 31% of the cohort). Outside that subgroup the enzalutamide effect collapses to RD ≈ +0.01.

**Other treatments** (abiraterone, docetaxel, olaparib, lu177-PSMA, pembrolizumab) show no main effect and no clinically meaningful subgroup effect — including refutation of the canonical biomarker pairings (olaparib×BRCA2, pembro×MSI-high, lu177-PSMA×PSMA-high).

